Month = {{DEC}},
Abstract = {{For centuries, healthcare has been a basic service provided by many
   governments to their citizens. Over the past few decades, we have
   witnessed a significant transformation in the quality of healthcare
   services provided by healthcare organizations and professionals. Recent
   advances have led to the emergence of Electronic Health (E-health),
   largely made possible by the massive deployment and adoption of
   information and communication technologies (ICTs). However,
   cybercriminals and attackers are exploiting vulnerabilities associated
   primarily with ICTs, causing data breaches of patients' confidential
   digital health information records. Here, we review recent security
   attacks reported for E-healthcare and discuss the solutions proposed to
   mitigate them. We also identify security challenges that must be
   addressed by E-health system designers and implementers in the future,
   to respond to threats that could arise as E-health systems become
   integrated with technologies such as cloud computing, the Internet of
   Things, and smart cities.}},
