Number = {{8}},
Pages = {{2089-2106}},
Month = {{AUG}},
Abstract = {{Electric vehicles (EVs), as their penetration increases, do not only
   challenge the sustainability of the power grid but also stimulate and
   promote its upgrading. Indeed, EVs can actively reinforce the
   development of the smart grid if their charging processes are properly
   coordinated through two-way communications, possibly benefiting all
   types of actors. Because grid systems involve a large number of actors
   with nonaligned objectives, we focus on the economic and incentive
   aspects, where each actor behaves in its own interest. We indeed believe
   that the market structure will directly impact the actors' behaviors,
   and as a result, the total benefits that the presence of EVs can earn in
   the society, hence the need for a careful design. This survey provides
   an overview of economic models considering unidirectional energy flows
   and bidirectional energy flows, i.e., with EVs temporarily providing
   energy to the grid. We describe and compare the main approaches,
   summarize the requirements on the supporting communication systems, and
   propose a classification to highlight the most important results and
   lacks.}},
